Politico=E2=80=99s Flight Club
------------------------

While Axios=E2=80=99s Mike Allen and Breitbart=E2=80=99s Matt Boyle took ce=
nter stage (or, really, stage right) as representatives of the =E2=80=9Cnew=
 media=E2=80=9D during the first White House press briefing, the most notab=
le absence in the briefing room, at least in D.C. media circles, was Dasha =
Burns, the former NBC News correspondent who was recently hired by Politico=
 to serve as its White House bureau chief and, more specifically, as its ma=
rquee star in the Trump era. Dasha was out sick=E2=80=94it happens=E2=80=94=
but the absence was also coincidentally symbolic.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

As I=E2=80=99ve noted, Politico=E2=80=99s core Washington coverage has been=
 aimless for some time, even as the business itself remains more than formi=
dable, with what I=E2=80=99m told is a more than 20 percent profit margin. =
Over a dozen reporters have left in recent months amid frustrations with ma=
nagement and the apparent general listlessness of the organization. Specifi=
cally, these folks have cited a lack of clarity and communication about Pol=
itico=E2=80=99s mission; frustration with a monotonous and confusing editin=
g process; a general sense that all but a few chosen reporters are underval=
ued; a negative newsroom atmosphere; and a diminished reputation with the T=
rump White House and Republicans, generally. (The front office has a very d=
ifferent take on all that, obviously.) Indeed, several outgoing reporters s=
aid Playbook, which is undergoing a transformation under newly appointed ma=
naging editor Jack Blanchard, had
become a punchline among Republicans.=C2=A0

Politico is undeniably an organization in transition. After Playbook co-aut=
hors Jake Sherman and Anna Palmer left to launch Punchbowl in 2021, Politic=
o=E2=80=99s leaders mostly sat on their hands and bitched while their lunch=
 was eaten thrice-daily on Capitol Hill. Recently, they have moved to launc=
h a new Capitol Hill enterprise and now publish their morning newsletter an=
 hour earlier than Punchbowl, which at least suggests a will to compete. At=
 the White House, they are pinning their hopes on Dasha, who is viewed inte=
rnally as a major get for the organization. Time will tell whether these we=
re the right bets.

Meanwhile, there have been some head-scratching decisions. It=E2=80=99s har=
d to understand why the company would offer star reporter and Playbook anch=
or Rachael Bade a raise only to move her off the product. And you don=E2=80=
=99t need to go to the Yale School of Management to understand why importin=
g Blanchard, a Brit who ran Politico=E2=80=99s U.K. operation, would piss o=
ff the scores of D.C. reporters who=E2=80=99d been secretly (and not so sec=
retly) pining to have their careers elevated by the Playbook platform. What=
=E2=80=99s more, the economics of the D.C. media business revolve around re=
aching the key opinion-formers on Capitol Hill=E2=80=94the members, yes, bu=
t also their comms and leg directors, and other staff. The last iteration o=
f Playbook was criticized for being voiceless and occasionally aimless, a f=
rankenproduct often cobbled together by anonymous digital producers in thei=
r twenties or thirties. Now it=E2=80=99s being run by an out-of-towner
with a pithy voice who doesn=E2=80=99t have connections on the Hill. If the=
 warm welcome the Brits received at the Washington Post is any kind of lead=
ing indicator, he=E2=80=99ll surely make some lifelong friends.

=C2=A0

The recent departure of Alex Isenstadt, the author of a new insider account=
 of the Trump campaign, magnified the troubles in Rosslyn, as D.C. media ty=
pes whisper loudly that Politico now has very few well-sourced Trump report=
ers. (This week they hired Jake Traylor, an NBC News Trump campaign embed. =
They=E2=80=99ve also hired Ben Jacobs, a journeyman political reporter.) Co=
ngressional reporter Daniella Diaz also left for NOTUS, a startup funded by=
 Robert Allbritton, Politico=E2=80=99s founder and former sole proprietor, =
who is now courting the rank and file at his former shop with the promise o=
f better pay and less editorial intervention. Notably, Politico=E2=80=99s l=
oyal, longtime communications chief Brad Dayspring=E2=80=94the man usually =
tasked with explaining to me why all the Politico defections don=E2=80=99t =
portend doom and gloom for the
organization=E2=80=94himself resigned on Wednesday after nearly a decade in=
 the job. (Dayspring will be at Politico through the end of March, and has =
yet to determine his next move, I=E2=80=99m told.)=C2=A0

In recent memos, Politico founding father and global E.I.C. John Harris has=
=C2=A0 touted various agenda-setting articles and alluded to the business=
=E2=80=99s plans to maintain its influence in Washington. Jonathan Greenber=
ger, its executive vice president and an ABC News alum, seems to believe th=
e organization will get there by bringing a television news mentality to th=
e digital news site, with =E2=80=9Cexecutive producers=E2=80=9D running var=
ious franchises and stars like Dasha in top roles. (Whether the E.P.s provi=
de leadership or merely another management layer remains to be seen.) Meanw=
hile, Alex Burns, the newsroom=E2=80=99s head of news, remains a frequent s=
capegoat for the rank and file=E2=80=99s complaints about management given =
his blunt and exacting demeanor. In any event, the verdict on Politico=E2=
=80=99s success in Trump=E2=80=99s Washington is still out.

