roader intention to arrogate more power to the executive branch and sidelin=
e Congress. Democrats are taking a cautious mini-victory lap for now, but n=
o one on Capitol Hill thinks Trump is going to start operating within the c=
onfines of the law, or precedent, as it pertains to Congress=E2=80=99s powe=
r of the purse.

=C2=A0

During his first nine days, Trump has outdone even himself, testing the bou=
nds of the presidency more quickly and aggressively than at any point durin=
g his first term. Just as notably, he=E2=80=99s pushed the envelope with th=
e tacit (and often explicit) approval of congressional Republicans, who hav=
e said almost nothing about his decision to ignore a bipartisan law banning=
 TikTok; to fire some 17 inspectors general without giving Congress 30 days=
=E2=80=99 notice; to purge the Justice Department of lawyers who worked on =
January 6 cases; and to fire members of the Equal Employment Opportunity Co=
mmission and the National Labor Relations Board=E2=80=94the latest in a ser=
ies of actions the president cannot legally execute.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Once again, we=E2=80=99re in shocking but not surprising territory. Trump w=
as elected, after all, on the promise that he would radically reshape the f=
ederal government and defang the =E2=80=9CDeep State.=E2=80=9D Indeed, the =
blueprint for the executive actions he=E2=80=99s taken in the past week had=
 been clearly spelled out in Project 2025, the Heritage Foundation=E2=80=99=
s 900-page governance agenda that Trump repeatedly disavowed on the campaig=
n trail. Now, of course, one of the project=E2=80=99s chief architects, Rus=
sell Vought, has been tapped to lead O.M.B.=C2=A0=C2=A0

Vought semi-foreshadowed these past nine days in Project 2025=E2=80=99s man=
ifesto on presidential power. =E2=80=9CThe great challenge confronting a co=
nservative president,=E2=80=9D Vought wrote ( https://static.project2025.or=
g/2025_MandateForLeadership_FULL.pdf?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Bright=
