stomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), =E2=80=9Cis the existential need=
 for aggressive use of the vast powers of the executive branch to return po=
wer=E2=80=94including power currently held by the executive branch=E2=80=94=
to the American people.=E2=80=9D So far, he=E2=80=99s only hitting the =E2=
=80=9Caggressive use=E2=80=9D part. Republican Senator Kevin Cramer, always=
 good for a dose of honesty, acknowledged that Trump is =E2=80=9Ctesting hi=
s power,=E2=80=9D adding that the Founders probably wouldn=E2=80=99t agree =
with such an expansive view of the presidency.

A Looming Congressional Clash
-----------------------------

The approach isn=E2=80=99t entirely novel: The =E2=80=9Cunitary executive=
=E2=80=9D theory has been rattling around conservative brains since at leas=
t the Reagan administration. But the notion that the president can remake t=
he federal government any way he likes=E2=80=94firing people, directing mon=
ey toward certain programs while unplugging others=E2=80=94has certainly pi=
cked up steam among conservatives looking for a champion to shake up what t=
hey see as a bloated bureaucracy unresponsive to the president=E2=80=99s wi=
ll. And yet the philosophy inevitably sets the stage for a constitutional c=
lash with Congress, especially over spending.

=C2=A0

Indeed, the =E2=80=9Cpower of the purse=E2=80=9D is so central to Congress=
=E2=80=99s very purpose that Senator Angus King, an independent who caucuse=
s with the Democrats, told reporters yesterday that if the directive to fre=
eze federal funding stood, =E2=80=9CCongress may as well adjourn.=E2=80=9D =
Democrats, of course, are in the minority and have little power to do anyth=
ing about it. And Republicans spent yesterday determined to sideline themse=
lves, largely waving away questions about Trump=E2=80=99s move to suspend f=
ederal grants that Congress had already allocated.=C2=A0

But as Mitchel Sollenberger, a constitutional law professor at the Universi=
ty of Michigan-Dearborn told me, even this isn=E2=80=99t new: Congress has =
been giving away its powers=E2=80=94to make war, institute tariffs, impose =
sanctions, etcetera=E2=80=94to the president for decades. =E2=80=9CThis shi=
p has never been righted. You haven=E2=80=99t been able to rebuild Humpty D=
umpty to the way Humpty Dumpty looked before he fell,=E2=80=9D he said.

There was some shock on Capitol Hill yesterday upon hearing that the admini=
stration would halt government grants before Vought was even confirmed as O=
=2EM.B. director. But the episode do=
esn=E2=80=99t seem to have dimmed Vought=
=E2=80=99s chances: Trump and his team are confident in their ability to la=
nd him the job. Plus, they have a backup plan. =E2=80=9CRecess appointments=
,=E2=80=9D by which Trump might bypass the Senate=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cadvise=
 and consent=E2=80=9D role on nominees, haven=E2=80=99t been a live discuss=
ion since Trump first brought it up in November=E2=80=94but it would be unl=
ike Trump not to keep the option in his back pocket.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Yet the Hill has mustered some mild bipartisan pushback, at least on the ma=
tter of the fired inspectors general. Iowa Republican Senator Chuck Grassle=
y, the 91-year-old chair of the Judiciary Committee, has been a defender of=
 inspectors general for decades, stemming from his own distrust of the gove=
rnment dating back to the Ruby Ridge standoff involving the F.B.I. in the 1=
990s. Grassley believes nonpartisan investigators are a check on federal ag=
encies, and he held up two of Trump=E2=80=99s political appointments after =
Trump fired five inspectors general in his first term.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Grassley hasn=E2=80=99t taken such drastic measures yet, but he and his Dem=
ocratic counterpart on the Judiciary Committee, Senator Dick Durbin, shot o=
ff a letter to the president asking that he provide Congress with the =E2=
=80=9Csubstantive rationale, including detailed and case-specific reasons=
=E2=80=9D for the firings. The letter is meant to open the conversation wit=
h the president on the issue, but I=E2=80=99m skeptical that Trump will res=
pond.=C2=A0

All presidents try to expand their power, of course, but Trump believes he =
has Congress and the Supreme Court behind him=E2=80=94and he could be right=
=2E A little more than a week into T=
rump II, one thing=E2=80=99s already clea=
r, as Stephen Griffin, who teaches constitutional law at Tulane, told me: =
=E2=80=9CConstitutionally, we=E2=80=99re looking at a very volatile situati=
