<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; wo=
rd-break: break-word;">
<tbody><tr>
<td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;">
<div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;=
Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:15=
0%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">While Axios=E2=80=99s <strong>M=
ike Allen</strong> and Breitbart=E2=80=99s <strong>Matt Boyle </strong>took=
 center stage (or, really, stage right) as representatives of the =E2=80=9C=
new media=E2=80=9D during the first White House press briefing, the most no=
table absence in the briefing room, at least in D.C. media circles, was <st=
rong>Dasha Burns</strong>, the former NBC News correspondent who was recent=
ly hired by Politico to serve as its White House bureau chief and, more spe=
cifically, as its marquee star in the Trump era. Dasha was out sick=E2=80=
=94it happens=E2=80=94but the absence was also coincidentally symbolic.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">As I=E2=80=99ve noted, Politico=
=E2=80=99s core Washington coverage has been aimless for some time, even as=
 the business itself remains more than formidable, with what I=E2=80=99m to=
ld is a more than 20 percent profit margin. Over a dozen reporters have lef=
t in recent months amid frustrations with management and the apparent gener=
al listlessness of the organization. Specifically, these folks have cited a=
 lack of clarity and communication about Politico=E2=80=99s mission; frustr=
ation with a monotonous and confusing editing process; a general sense that=
 all but a few <em>chosen</em> reporters are undervalued; a negative newsro=
om atmosphere; and a diminished reputation with the Trump White House and R=
epublicans, generally. (The front office has a very different take on all t=
hat, <em>obviously</em>.) Indeed, several outgoing reporters said Playbook,=
 which is undergoing a transformation under newly appointed managing editor=
 <strong>Jack Blanchard</strong>, had
become a punchline among Republicans.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;"><br/>Politico is undeniably an =
organization in transition. After Playbook co-authors <strong>Jake Sherman<=
/strong> and <strong>Anna Palmer</strong> left to launch Punchbowl in 2021,=
 Politico=E2=80=99s leaders mostly sat on their hands and bitched while the=
ir lunch was eaten thrice-daily on Capitol Hill. Recently, they have moved =
to launch a new Capitol Hill enterprise and now publish their morning newsl=
etter an hour earlier than Punchbowl, which at least suggests a will to com=
pete. At the White House, they are pinning their hopes on Dasha, who is vie=
wed internally as a major get for the organization. Time will tell whether =
these were the right bets.<br/><br/></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Meanwhile, there have been some=
 head-scratching decisions. It=E2=80=99s hard to understand why the company=
 would offer star reporter and Playbook anchor <strong>Rachael Bade </stron=
g>a raise only to move her off the product. And you don=E2=80=99t need to g=
o to the Yale School of Management to understand why importing Blanchard, a=
 Brit who ran Politico=E2=80=99s U.K. operation, would piss off the scores =
of D.C. reporters who=E2=80=99d been secretly (and not so secretly) pining =
to have their careers elevated by the Playbook platform. What=E2=80=99s mor=
e, the economics of the D.C. media business revolve around reaching the key=
 opinion-formers on Capitol Hill=E2=80=94the members, yes, but also their c=
omms and leg directors, and other staff. The last iteration of Playbook was=
 criticized for being voiceless and occasionally aimless, a frankenproduct =
often cobbled together by anonymous digital producers in their twenties or =
thirties. Now it=E2=80=99s being run by an out-of-towner
with a pithy voice who doesn=E2=80=99t have connections on the Hill. If the=
 warm welcome the Brits received at the <em>Washington Post</em> is any kin=
d of leading indicator, he=E2=80=99ll surely make some lifelong friends.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">The recent departure of <strong=
>Alex Isenstadt</strong>, the author of a new insider account of the Trump =
campaign, magnified the troubles in Rosslyn, as D.C. media types whisper lo=
udly that Politico now has very few<em> </em>well-sourced Trump reporters. =
(This week they hired <strong>Jake Traylor</strong>, an NBC News Trump camp=
aign embed. They=E2=80=99ve also hired <strong>Ben Jacobs</strong>, a journ=
eyman political reporter.) Congressional reporter <strong>Daniella Diaz </s=
trong>also left for NOTUS, a startup funded by <strong>Robert Allbritton</s=
trong>, Politico=E2=80=99s founder and former sole proprietor, who is now c=
ourting the rank and file at his former shop with the promise of better pay=
 and less editorial intervention. Notably, Politico=E2=80=99s loyal, longti=
me communications chief <strong>Brad Dayspring</strong>=E2=80=94the man usu=
ally tasked with explaining to me why all the Politico defections <em>don=
=E2=80=99t</em> portend doom and gloom for the
organization=E2=80=94himself resigned on Wednesday after nearly a decade in=
 the job. (Dayspring will be at Politico through the end of March, and has =
yet to determine his next move, I=E2=80=99m told.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0;"><br/>In recent memos, Politico founding father and =
global E.I.C. <strong>John Harris </strong>has=C2=A0 touted various agenda-=
setting articles and alluded to the business=E2=80=99s plans to maintain it=
s influence in Washington. <strong>Jonathan Greenberger</strong>, its execu=
tive vice president and an ABC News alum, seems to believe the organization=
 will get there by bringing a television news mentality to the digital news=
 site, with =E2=80=9Cexecutive producers=E2=80=9D running various franchise=
s and stars like Dasha in top roles. (Whether the E.P.s provide leadership =
or merely another management layer remains to be seen.) Meanwhile, <strong>=
Alex Burns</strong>, the newsroom=E2=80=99s head of news, remains a frequen=
t scapegoat for the rank and file=E2=80=99s complaints about management giv=
en his blunt and exacting demeanor. In any event, the verdict on Politico=
=E2=80=99s success in Trump=E2=80=99s Washington is still out.</p>
</div>
