<table class=3D"heading_block block-2" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadd=
ing=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace=
: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<tbody><tr>
<td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;padding-left:24px;padding-right:24px;text-=
align:center;width:100%;">
<h3 style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; direction: ltr; font-family: &#39;P=
uckSerifDisplay&#39;,&#39;Georgia&#39;; font-size: 24px; font-weight: 700; =
letter-spacing: normal; line-height: 120%; text-align: center; margin-top: =
0; margin-bottom: 0; mso-line-height-alt: 28.799999999999997px;"><strong>A =
Looming Congressional Clash</strong></h3>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; wo=
rd-break: break-word;">
<tbody><tr>
<td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;">
<div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;=
Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:15=
0%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">The approach isn=E2=80=99t enti=
rely novel: The =E2=80=9Cunitary executive=E2=80=9D theory has been rattlin=
g around conservative brains since at least the <strong>Reagan</strong> adm=
inistration. But the notion that the president can remake the federal gover=
nment any way he likes=E2=80=94firing people, directing money toward certai=
n programs while unplugging others=E2=80=94has certainly picked up steam am=
ong conservatives looking for a champion to shake up what they see as a blo=
ated bureaucracy unresponsive to the president=E2=80=99s will. And yet the =
philosophy inevitably sets the stage for a constitutional clash with Congre=
ss, especially over spending.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Indeed, the =E2=80=9Cpower of t=
he purse=E2=80=9D is so central to Congress=E2=80=99s very purpose that Sen=
ator <strong>Angus King</strong>, an independent who caucuses with the Demo=
crats, told reporters yesterday that if the directive to freeze federal fun=
ding stood, =E2=80=9CCongress may as well adjourn.=E2=80=9D Democrats, of c=
ourse, are in the minority and have little power to do anything about it. A=
nd Republicans spent yesterday determined to sideline themselves, largely w=
aving away questions about Trump=E2=80=99s move to suspend federal grants t=
hat Congress had already allocated.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;"><br/>But as <strong>Mitchel Sol=
lenberger</strong>, a constitutional law professor at the University of Mic=
higan-Dearborn told me, even this isn=E2=80=99t new: Congress has been givi=
ng away its powers=E2=80=94to make war, institute tariffs, impose sanctions=
, etcetera=E2=80=94to the president for decades. =E2=80=9CThis ship has nev=
er been righted. You haven=E2=80=99t been able to rebuild Humpty Dumpty to =
the way Humpty Dumpty looked before he fell,=E2=80=9D he said.<br/><br/></p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">There was some shock on Capitol=
 Hill yesterday upon hearing that the administration would halt government =
grants before Vought was even confirmed as O.M.B. director. But the episode=
 doesn=E2=80=99t seem to have dimmed Vought=E2=80=99s chances: Trump and hi=
s team are confident in their ability to land him the job. Plus, they have =
a backup plan. =E2=80=9CRecess appointments,=E2=80=9D by which Trump might =
bypass the Senate=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cadvise and consent=E2=80=9D role on no=
minees, haven=E2=80=99t been a live discussion since Trump first brought it=
 up in November=E2=80=94but it would be unlike Trump not to keep the option=
 in his back pocket.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Yet the Hill <em>has </em>muste=
red some mild bipartisan pushback, at least on the matter of the fired insp=
ectors general. Iowa Republican Senator <strong>Chuck Grassley</strong>, th=
e 91-year-old chair of the Judiciary Committee, has been a defender of insp=
ectors general for decades, stemming from his own distrust of the governmen=
t dating back to the Ruby Ridge standoff involving the F.B.I. in the 1990s.=
 Grassley believes nonpartisan investigators are a check on federal agencie=
s, and he held up two of Trump=E2=80=99s political appointments after Trump=
 fired five inspectors general in his first term.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0px;">Grassley hasn=E2=80=99t taken s=
uch drastic measures <em>yet</em>, but he and his Democratic counterpart on=
 the Judiciary Committee, Senator <strong>Dick Durbin</strong>, shot off a =
letter to the president asking that he provide Congress with the =E2=80=9Cs=
ubstantive rationale, including detailed and case-specific reasons=E2=80=9D=
 for the firings. The letter is meant to open the conversation with the pre=
sident on the issue, but I=E2=80=99m skeptical that Trump will respond.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 0;"><br/>All presidents try to expand their power, of c=
ourse, but Trump believes he has Congress and the Supreme Court behind him=
=E2=80=94and he could be right. A little more than a week into Trump II, on=
e thing=E2=80=99s already clear, as <strong>Stephen Griffin</strong>, who t=
eaches<strong> </strong>constitutional law at Tulane, told me: =E2=80=9CCon=
stitutionally, we=E2=80=99re looking at a very volatile situation.=E2=80=9D=
 =C2=A0</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
